The '''hooded visorbearer''' ('''''Augastes lumachella''''') is a small species of [[hummingbird]] in the family [[Trochilidae]]. [[Endemic]] to the east [[Brazil]]ian state of [[Bahia]], it is found only at higher altitudes in the [[Chapada Diamantina]] region. The species is [[sexually dimorphic]]. 
It resides in the [[campos rupestres|campo rupestre]], an arid, high-elevation area characterized by rocky outcrops, poor soils, open habitats, and harsh climatic conditions. There, it feeds primarily on nectar, though it also takes insects. Its breeding ecology remains largely undescribed, though it is known to build its nest from cactus spines. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] rates it as a [[near-threatened]] species, primarily because of the relatively small size of its range. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]], brought about primarily by unregulated mining and the conversion of the campo to pastureland and human habitation. Climate change is projected to cause a major contraction of its range – perhaps by as much as 90%.

==Taxonomy and systematics==
[[File:MonographTrochi4Goul 0086.jpg|thumb|upright|Hooded visorbearer ([[lithography]] by [[Henry Constantine Richter]] (1821–1902) based on a drawing by [[John Gould]] (1804–1881))]]
[[Rene Primevere Lesson]] first [[species description|described]] the hooded visorbearer for science in 1838, using a specimen collected in [[Bahia]], Brazil.{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}{{sfn|Lesson|1838|p=315}} He named it ''Ornismya lumachella''.{{sfn|Lesson|1838|p=315}} Five years later, Lesson moved it and four other species to his newly created genus ''[[Amazilis]]''.{{sfn|Lesson|1843|p=758}} [[John Gould]] moved it again in 1849, when he created the genus ''[[Augastes]]'' for this species and the [[hyacinth visorbearer]], another east Brazilian endemic. There are no subspecies.{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} [[DNA studies]] have shown that the two ''Augastes'' hummingbirds are [[sister species]], and that the genus is most closely related to [[Geoffroy's daggerbill]].{{sfn|Chaves|Vasconcelos|Freitas|Santos|2020|p=1060}}

The genus name ''Augastes'' comes directly from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''augastes'', meaning "radiant" or "light-giver".{{sfn|Jobling|2010|p=60}} The species name ''lumachella'' is an Italian word for [[fire marble]] – a dark limestone that contains [[fossil]]ised shells; it is a diminutive of the word for snail (''lumacha'').{{sfn|Jobling|2010|p=232}} Although the species name is sometimes written as ''lumachellus'' rather than ''lumachella'', this is incorrect; because it is an Italian word (rather than a Latinized one), it is considered to be invariable.{{sfn|Schuchmann|1999|p=660}}

==Description==
The hooded visorbearer is a small hummingbird, measuring {{convert|8.3|-|10|cm|abbr=on}} in length and weighing {{convert|4|-|4.8|g|oz|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Schuchmann|1999|p=660}}{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|p=170}} Its short, straight [[beak|bill]] is black.{{sfn|Schuchmann|1999|p=660}} The species is moderately [[sexually dimorphic]]. The male is an [[iridescent]] bronzy-green color on the upperparts and underparts.{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} His forehead and throat are an iridescent golden-green with a narrow border of bluish-green at the lower edge of the throat.{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}}{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} The sides and {{birdgloss|crown}} of his head are black, and a thin line of black borders his [[gorget (bird)|gorget]]. He has a narrow white breast band with a golden-orange spot in the center and purplish-brown wings.{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} His tail is a deep bronzy-crimson.{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} The female's coloring is more subdued. She is more bronzy on her upperparts and underparts, and her head is green instead of black.{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} She has a gray face and the sides of her head are brown, rather than black.{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}} The green on her throat is less colorful and iridescent than that of the male's, with a stronger border of bluish-green at the lower edge; the color does not extend to her forehead. Immature birds are bronzy-green above and brown below, with a white throat speckled with green. Their tails are a coppery-bronze above and crimson below, less brilliantly-colored than those of adults.{{sfn|Gould|1861|p=Plate 222}} The combination of head pattern and tail color is said to make this species "unmistakable" within its small natural range.{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|p=170}}

===Voice===
The song of the hooded visorbearer is described as "nasal" and "dry". Transcribed as ''tru tweé tru zee'', its short phrases are typically repeated more than three times in a row.{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|p=170}}

==Range and habitat==
The hooded visorbearer is endemic to eastern [[Brazil]].{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} Found only in the [[Chapada Diamantina]] region of [[Bahia]], it is restricted to [[campos rupestres|campo rupestre]],{{sfn|Paganucci de Queiroz|Rapini|Giulietti|2006|p=102}} a high-elevation [[ecoregion]] that is characterized by poor soils, open vegetation, rocky outcrops and harsh climatic conditions.{{sfn|Parrini|Raposo|Pacheco|Carvalhães|1999|p=89}} Its occurs at elevations ranging from {{convert|900|to|2000|m|abbr=on}},{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|p=170}}{{sfn|Paganucci de Queiroz|Rapini|Giulietti|2006|p=102}} and is considered to be one of South America's [[wikt:obligate|obligate]] grassland birds.{{sfn|Vickery|Tubaro|Cardoso da Silva|Peterjohn|1999|p=14}} It is found in rocky, semi-arid areas with cactus and low shrubs on the summits of mountains and mesas.{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|p=170}}{{sfn|Souza|2006|p=128}}

==Behavior==
===Feeding===
Like all hummingbirds, the hooded visorbearer feeds primarily on [[nectar]], though it will also take insects. It typically forages low, often less than {{convert|1|m|abbr=on}} from the ground.{{sfn|Schuchmann|1999|p=660}} It is known to visit ''[[Vriesea]]'' flowers early in the day, while the flowers (which are primarily bat-pollinated) still hold some residual nectar.{{sfn|Sazima|Buzato|Sazima|1995|p=33}}

===Breeding===
[[File:Augastes lumachella.jpg|thumb|upright|Nesting]]
Little is known of the breeding ecology of the hooded visorbearer. It builds its [[bird nest|nest]] from cactus spines, usually about a metre (just over three feet) off the ground.{{sfn|Wheatley|2021}}

==Conservation and threats==
For several decades in the 20th century, the species was thought to have gone [[extinct species|extinct]]. Then, in 1961, Brazilian naturalist [[Augusto Ruschi]] led an expedition to an area where they had been [[bird collections|collected]] in the past, and rediscovered them.{{sfn|Almeida|Raposo|1999|p=69–70}} The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] now rates the hooded visorbearer as a [[near-threatened species]], based primarily on its relatively small range.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2020}} The decline of suitable habitat in both size and quality is ongoing, primarily as a result of uncontrolled fires and climate change. Projections suggest that the visorbearer's range may shrink by as much as 90% by 2060 due to the effects of climage change.{{sfn|Wheatley|2021}} The mining of gold, diamonds, quartz and manganese within its range detrimentally affects habitat, as does the conversion of natural areas to animal pasturage and human habitation.{{sfn|Wheatley|2021}} Although its population has not been quantified, its numbers are thought to be declining.{{sfn|Wheatley|2021}}

==Relationship with humans==
The hooded visorbearer is considered to be among the handful of birds in the Chapada Diamantina that prove particularly attractive to [[Birdwatching|birdwatcher]]s. Trails have been created in the [[Chapada Diamantina National Park]] to enable ecotourists to enter the habitat in which they are found.{{sfn|Góes Coelho|Graco Machado|Santana de Carvalho|Csekö Nolasco|2008|p=53}}

